<DocsLayout
  title="Project knowledge"
  eyebrow="Capabilities"
  description="Markdown-backed project documents the agent can search and revise."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/memories/", title: "Memory & embeddings" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/media-generation/", title: "Media generation" }}
>
  <p>
    Project knowledge is for durable documents: requirements, decisions, research notes,
    runbooks, artifact references, and longer narrative memory. The first engine,
    <code>roder-ext-knowledge-md</code>, stores each document as markdown with YAML front
    matter so humans can browse, diff, and edit it outside Roder.
  </p>

  <h2>Agent tools</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>knowledge_list</code>, <code>knowledge_read</code>, and <code>knowledge_search</code> browse the corpus.</li>
    <li><code>knowledge_save</code>, <code>knowledge_update</code>, and <code>knowledge_delete</code> create revisions or archive documents.</li>
    <li><code>knowledge_link</code> records typed relationships such as supersedes, contradicts, duplicates, or relates_to.</li>
  </ul>

  <pre><code>roder knowledge list --kind decision
roder knowledge search "release process" --include-global
roder knowledge save --kind runbook --title "Deploy checklist" "Body text"
roder knowledge revisions kn-123</code></pre>

  <h2>Recall</h2>
  <p>
    When enabled, knowledge recall injects a bounded set of relevant documents as cited
    context blocks and points the model at <code>knowledge_read</code> for full bodies.
    Memories remain short atomic facts; knowledge documents are larger, typed, revised,
    and linked.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`[knowledge]
enabled = true
backend = "markdown"
recall = true
recall_limit = 4`}</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
